TY  - JOUR
T1  - Uncertainty, Entrepreneurship, and Sharecropping in India
Y1  - 1971/05/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259769
DO  - 10.1086/259769
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 578
EP  - 595
VL  - 79
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This study attempts to explain the coexistence of different farm lease arrangements in terms of the varying significance of entrepreneurial functions. In India, crop-sharing arrangements are common in areas of relative economic certainty with very little scope for decision making, for example, for product and factor substitution, and where the entrepreneurial profit is low. Fixed-cash rents are common in situations of high uncertainty where the scope for decision making is significant or where the crops are highly profitable. Efficiency considerations predominate in areas of sharecropping, favoring a smaller farm size, whereas, under high uncertainty, large size is favored for reducing risk.
AB  - This study attempts to explain the coexistence of different farm lease arrangements in terms of the varying significance of entrepreneurial functions. In India, crop-sharing arrangements are common in areas of relative economic certainty with very little scope for decision making, for example, for product and factor substitution, and where the entrepreneurial profit is low. Fixed-cash rents are common in situations of high uncertainty where the scope for decision making is significant or where the crops are highly profitable. Efficiency considerations predominate in areas of sharecropping, favoring a smaller farm size, whereas, under high uncertainty, large size is favored for reducing risk.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259769
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259769
Y2  - 2024/03/22
