TY  - JOUR
T1  - American Inventiveness, 1870-1920
AU  - Higgs, Robert
Y1  - 1971/05/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259775
DO  - 10.1086/259775
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 661
EP  - 667
VL  - 79
IS  - 3
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper extends the wealth-maximization model of invention in a new direction by taking into account the costs of information and by relating those costs to the urban-rural distribution of the population. The major empirical finding, obtained through a multiple regression analysis, is that the proportion of the population in urban areas and the number of inventions per capita were closely associated during the 1870-1920 period for a cross section of American states. This finding may well be significant for the explanation of economic growth as a self-sustaining process.
AB  - This paper extends the wealth-maximization model of invention in a new direction by taking into account the costs of information and by relating those costs to the urban-rural distribution of the population. The major empirical finding, obtained through a multiple regression analysis, is that the proportion of the population in urban areas and the number of inventions per capita were closely associated during the 1870-1920 period for a cross section of American states. This finding may well be significant for the explanation of economic growth as a self-sustaining process.
